<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,656,1150]" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,227,873,899]" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Notes:</emphasis>
This taxon is known from northern 
<collectingCountry box="[632,699,872,898]" name="Spain" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Spain</collectingCountry>
, and so its presence was considered unlikely in southwestern 
<collectingCountry name="Portugal" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Portugal</collectingCountry>
, and the material from 2015 was confused with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perez" authorityYear="1895" box="[797,939,908,935]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="212" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leptopyga">
<emphasis box="[797,939,908,935]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">A. leptopyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which is present elsewhere in 
<collectingCountry box="[1284,1383,908,934]" name="Portugal" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Portugal</collectingCountry>
. The true presence of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kirby" baseAuthorityYear="1802" box="[385,542,944,971]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="212" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barbilabris">
<emphasis box="[385,542,944,971]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">A. barbilabris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[578,673,944,970]" name="Portugal" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Portugal</collectingCountry>
solves two mysteries, namely the presence of 
<taxonomicName authority="Smith, 1845" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1845" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Sphecodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="212" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pellucidus">
<emphasis box="[1196,1436,944,970]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Sphecodes pellucidus</emphasis>
Smith, 1845
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Herrich-Schaffer, 1839" authorityName="Herrich-Schaffer" authorityYear="1839" box="[388,885,980,1007]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Nomada" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="212" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alboguttata">
<emphasis box="[388,618,980,1006]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Nomada alboguttata</emphasis>
Herrich-Schäffer, 1839
</taxonomicName>
, both of which are brood parasites strongly, if not obligately, associated with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kirby" baseAuthorityYear="1802" box="[499,656,1016,1043]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="212" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barbilabris">
<emphasis box="[499,656,1016,1043]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">A. barbilabris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Bogusch, P. &amp; Straka, J." box="[670,942,1016,1043]" pageId="11" pageNumber="212" pagination="1 - 41" refId="ref20454" refString="Bogusch, P. &amp; Straka, J. (2012) Review and identification of the cuckoo bees of central Europe (Hymenoptera: Halictidae: Sphecodes). Zootaxa, 3311 (1), 1 - 41. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3311.1.1" type="journal article" year="2012">Bogusch &amp; Straka 2012</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Smit, J." box="[952,1073,1016,1043]" pageId="11" pageNumber="212" pagination="1 - 253" refId="ref23012" refString="Smit, J. (2018) Identification key to the European species of the bee genus Nomada Scopoli, 1770 (Hymenoptera: Apidae), including 23 new species. Entomofauna, Monographie 3, 1 - 253." type="journal article" year="2018">Smit 2018</bibRefCitation>
). The presence of this seemingly isolated population in the Algarve is surprising, but as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Herrich-Schaffer" authorityYear="1839" box="[815,977,1052,1078]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Nomada" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="212" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alboguttata">
<emphasis box="[815,977,1052,1078]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">N. alboguttata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been reported from the 
<collectingRegion box="[1295,1379,1052,1078]" country="Portugal" name="Setubal" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Setúbal</collectingRegion>
peninsula (
<bibRefCitation author="Baldock, D. &amp; Wood, T. J. &amp; Cross, I. &amp; Smit, J." box="[279,504,1088,1115]" pageId="11" pageNumber="212" pagination="1 - 164" refId="ref20369" refString="Baldock, D., Wood, T. J., Cross, I. &amp; Smit, J. (2018) The Bees of Portugal. Entomofauna, Supplement 22, 1 - 164." type="journal article" year="2018">
Baldock 
<emphasis box="[381,430,1088,1114]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">et al</emphasis>
. 2018
</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kirby" baseAuthorityYear="1802" box="[523,680,1088,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="212" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barbilabris">
<emphasis box="[523,680,1088,1115]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">A. barbilabris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is probably more widespread in 
<collectingCountry box="[1046,1141,1088,1114]" name="Portugal" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Portugal</collectingCountry>
but under-recorded due to its early flight period.
</paragraph>
